I'll probably scoot that
forward a little bit.

00:36:35.160 --> 00:36:38.067
Just not take up too much time.

00:36:38.067 --> 00:36:39.900
This is what it's like
to be on set with us.

00:36:39.900 --> 00:36:42.780
This is our director, Taylor
Steele, holding a beer,

00:36:42.780 --> 00:36:45.900
trying to explain to two of
some of the most stylish surfers

00:36:45.900 --> 00:36:47.449
how to surf together.

00:36:47.449 --> 00:36:49.740
So with this project, we try
to think of different ways

00:36:49.740 --> 00:36:51.014
to enhance the experience.

00:36:51.014 --> 00:36:52.680
One of the things we
did is we partnered

00:36:52.680 --> 00:36:54.990
each one of the surfers
with a different artist.

00:36:54.990 --> 00:36:57.480
So when we premiered
the project,

00:36:57.480 --> 00:36:58.980
we rented out a
gallery in New York,

00:36:58.980 --> 00:37:02.060
and we had all the boards
from the project on display.

00:37:02.060 --> 00:37:03.740
We had photos from
the book on display.

00:37:03.740 --> 00:37:05.970
We had a full virtual
reality room set up.

00:37:05.970 --> 00:37:08.640
So anywhere you went,
we had a team that

00:37:08.640 --> 00:37:10.570
would film virtual reality.

00:37:10.570 --> 00:37:12.630
And we thought of different
ways that we could

00:37:12.630 --> 00:37:14.290
enhance the viewer experience.

00:37:14.290 --> 00:37:16.620
And we thought, well, everyone
says surfing's a dance.

00:37:16.620 --> 00:37:19.200
Let's get these two to
dance on a wave together.

00:37:19.200 --> 00:37:22.680
So this is our director, trying
to explain to them how to dance

00:37:22.680 --> 00:37:25.160
together with beer in hand.

00:37:25.160 --> 00:37:26.820
The photos are all
shiny and polished,

00:37:26.820 --> 00:37:28.357
but really, we're having fun.

00:37:28.357 --> 00:37:29.190
We're going camping.

00:37:29.190 --> 00:37:30.023
We're going surfing.

00:37:30.023 --> 00:37:32.190
We're trying not to take
ourselves too seriously.

00:37:32.190 --> 00:37:34.110
So this is a result of that.

00:37:34.110 --> 00:37:35.910
They went and did
it seven different--

00:37:35.910 --> 00:37:38.314
they went and turned
seven times on this wave.

00:37:38.314 --> 00:37:40.230
Actually, this is the
second time they did it.

00:37:40.230 --> 00:37:43.445
The first time was better for
the film, and they came in.

00:37:43.445 --> 00:37:45.570
And me being the photographer,
I'm like, hey, guys.

00:37:45.570 --> 00:37:46.700
Like, that was amazing.

00:37:46.700 --> 00:37:48.200
But I just didn't get the photo.

00:37:48.200 --> 00:37:50.432
Can you guys wait for it
to get a little bit darker

00:37:50.432 --> 00:37:51.390
and we'll try it again?

00:37:51.390 --> 00:37:53.640
I really want to shoot it,
like, at tenth of a second.

00:37:53.640 --> 00:37:56.280
I want to make it slow
everything down and kind

00:37:56.280 --> 00:37:58.840
of give it that panning feel.

00:37:58.840 --> 00:38:00.990
There's an old
ballet photo that I

00:38:00.990 --> 00:38:03.150
saw that made me think
of motion and dance,

00:38:03.150 --> 00:38:07.162
and so this was my
version of that.

00:38:07.162 --> 00:38:09.120
AUDIENCE: So are you in
the water [INAUDIBLE]??

00:38:09.120 --> 00:38:10.920
TODD GLASER: I was on
the land for this one.

00:38:10.920 --> 00:38:11.280
Yeah.

00:38:11.280 --> 00:38:13.113
AUDIENCE: Do you have
a tripod [INAUDIBLE]??

00:38:13.113 --> 00:38:17.320
TODD GLASER: I have a tripod
and a big telephoto lens.

00:38:17.320 --> 00:38:19.010
And you know, at
this point break,

00:38:19.010 --> 00:38:20.280
it's a really long point
break, and you don't

00:38:20.280 --> 00:38:21.404
get a lot of opportunities.

00:38:21.404 --> 00:38:25.784
So a lot of the times with the
waves that surf really well,

00:38:25.784 --> 00:38:27.700
they don't necessarily
photograph really well.

00:38:27.700 --> 00:38:30.060
So a lot of times, you're
trying to pick and choose

00:38:30.060 --> 00:38:31.650
what's going to photograph
better than what's

00:38:31.650 --> 00:38:32.733
going to surf really well.

00:38:32.733 --> 00:38:35.320
So if you go catch
a two-minute wave,

00:38:35.320 --> 00:38:37.020
it's terrible for photography.

00:38:37.020 --> 00:38:39.120
But if you can catch a
five-second wave 50 times,

00:38:39.120 --> 00:38:42.460
you have a lot more
opportunity to make moments.

