we're exploring,
but we want everyone

00:40:03.670 --> 00:40:05.890
to be able to come home
safely to their families.

00:40:05.890 --> 00:40:09.430
And have a good story to share,
and make you want to go travel.

00:40:09.430 --> 00:40:12.940
This is a wave that we
found up in northern Europe.

00:40:12.940 --> 00:40:14.500
None of us had
been there before,

00:40:14.500 --> 00:40:17.050
and we forecasted this trip.

00:40:17.050 --> 00:40:19.060
A friend of mine had been
there, and he wrote me

00:40:19.060 --> 00:40:20.810
directions on a napkin.

00:40:20.810 --> 00:40:22.310
And he called me
about a week later.

00:40:22.310 --> 00:40:23.420
He's like, I think it's
going to be good there.

00:40:23.420 --> 00:40:24.040
So I called.

00:40:24.040 --> 00:40:25.799
And it's one thing to
call on a surf trip.

00:40:25.799 --> 00:40:27.340
It's another thing
to call these guys

00:40:27.340 --> 00:40:29.380
from their home in
their personal lives,

00:40:29.380 --> 00:40:31.810
and then get a 14-man
film crew to go as well.

00:40:31.810 --> 00:40:33.500
So there's kind of
a bit of pressure

00:40:33.500 --> 00:40:35.160
when you're making those calls.

00:40:35.160 --> 00:40:37.040
We got skunked for
the first three days.

00:40:37.040 --> 00:40:39.040
We ended up going to a
bar, and we called Kelly.

00:40:39.040 --> 00:40:39.610
We were like, Kelly.

00:40:39.610 --> 00:40:40.120
Here we are.

00:40:40.120 --> 00:40:41.490
Like, we don't know what to do.

00:40:41.490 --> 00:40:42.560
And he's like, I've
never been there.

00:40:42.560 --> 00:40:44.350
But like, if you can make
it to Portugal tomorrow,

00:40:44.350 --> 00:40:45.180
it's going to be good.

00:40:45.180 --> 00:40:46.150
And we're like, yeah, we can.

00:40:46.150 --> 00:40:47.191
We [? can't ?] move that.

00:40:47.191 --> 00:40:49.930
We flew to Europe and
had to drive 10 hours.

00:40:49.930 --> 00:40:53.140
And we ended up-- the next day,
we drove around and ended up

00:40:53.140 --> 00:40:55.660
finding this wave, and we
surfed it for two days totally

00:40:55.660 --> 00:40:56.570
by ourselves.

00:40:56.570 --> 00:41:00.355
So this is Shane and
Albee pushing each other

00:41:00.355 --> 00:41:02.171
in these conditions.

00:41:02.171 --> 00:41:03.670
When it comes to
shooting, you don't

00:41:03.670 --> 00:41:05.628
know how long these
sessions are going to last.

00:41:05.628 --> 00:41:07.600
So with a wide
angle, I went out.

00:41:07.600 --> 00:41:09.520
The water's probably
about 45 degrees.

00:41:09.520 --> 00:41:11.690
I shot three waves
from the water.

00:41:11.690 --> 00:41:12.925
This is one, that was two.

00:41:12.925 --> 00:41:14.300
And I figured, I
think we got it.

00:41:14.300 --> 00:41:16.175
And then went in and
kept shooting from land.

00:41:16.175 --> 00:41:16.750
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:16.750 --> 00:41:20.140
So with time-- with time and
experience comes knowing when

00:41:20.140 --> 00:41:22.756
you have it, knowing
when you don't.

00:41:22.756 --> 00:41:23.530
You know?

00:41:23.530 --> 00:41:24.920
A classic pub shot.

00:41:24.920 --> 00:41:27.301
So for these guys, we had
their conversation in a pub.

00:41:27.301 --> 00:41:27.800
Sorry, guys.

00:41:27.800 --> 00:41:28.870
I'm going to speed
up a little bit,

00:41:28.870 --> 00:41:30.953
because there's a section
I really want to get to.

00:41:30.953 --> 00:41:32.260
Rob Machado and Craig Anderson.

00:41:32.260 --> 00:41:34.240
We took them down to
[INAUDIBLE] Points.

00:41:34.240 --> 00:41:36.539
Two super stylish surfers.

00:41:36.539 --> 00:41:38.830
For anyone into photography,
the whole time while we're

00:41:38.830 --> 00:41:41.744
producing and trying to make
all these projects happen,

00:41:41.744 --> 00:41:42.910
we had a ton of camera gear.

00:41:42.910 --> 00:41:45.280
I always kept a Leica
35-millimeter camera

00:41:45.280 --> 00:41:45.915
around my neck.

00:41:45.915 --> 00:41:48.040
I was trying to scramble
to get all my camera gear.

00:41:48.040 --> 00:41:49.690
I looked up, and Rob and
Craig were checking it.

00:41:49.690 --> 00:41:50.315
I picked it up.

00:41:50.315 --> 00:41:51.790
I shot one photo on my Leica.

00:41:51.790 --> 00:41:53.620
It's a black and
white film photo.

00:41:53.620 --> 00:41:56.440
And this is a wave that we
found four days of driving

00:41:56.440 --> 00:41:58.030
12 hours a day without surfing.

00:41:58.030 --> 00:41:59.910
We hadn't surfed up
until this point.

00:41:59.910 --> 00:42:04.700
And we finally jumped a fence,
and this is what we found.

00:42:04.700 --> 00:42:08.652
A couple portraits of Craig,
giving a sense of setting.

00:42:08.652 --> 00:42:10.390
You know, once you
have the land shot,

00:42:10.390 --> 00:42:13.180
once you have the water shot,
you know, the portrait shots,

00:42:13.180 --> 00:42:15.580
you try and give it kind of
an intimate look at what it's

00:42:15.580 --> 00:42:17.780
like to take off down the line.

00:42:17.780 --> 00:42:20.626
So these are all images that
were all shot in one day.

00:42:20.626 --> 00:42:22.000
So when we're
shooting, you know,

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:24.070
I'm constantly running
a mental checklist of,

00:42:24.070 --> 00:42:26.167
like, how can we
tell this whole story

00:42:26.167 --> 00:42:27.250
in a short amount of time?

00:42:27.250 --> 00:42:29.458
Because we don't know how
long this is going to last.

00:42:29.458 --> 00:42:31.340
We'd been totally
skunked for days.

00:42:31.340 --> 00:42:33.250
This turned into
our winter section.

00:42:33.250 --> 00:42:34.810
And we realized, you know what?

00:42:34.810 --> 00:42:37.030
It doesn't quite
feel like winter,

00:42:37.030 --> 00:42:40.355
so we need to do one more trip,
which was a hard one to explain

00:42:40.355 --> 00:42:42.590
to everyone to get done.

00:42:42.590 --> 00:42:45.700
So we ended up chasing
a blizzard to the most

00:42:45.700 --> 00:42:48.460
northern islands in Japan.

00:42:48.460 --> 00:42:50.210
And I thought it
was a great idea.

00:42:50.210 --> 00:42:51.870
I was sitting in
Hawaii at the time.

00:42:51.870 --> 00:42:54.640
It was, like, five days before
Christmas, and we're like,

00:42:54.640 --> 00:42:56.260
we have five days
before Christmas.

00:42:56.260 --> 00:42:58.810
I think we can do this
trip in three days.

00:42:58.810 --> 00:42:59.920
Fly to Japan.

00:42:59.920 --> 00:43:01.930
We drove in a blizzard
for two days, surfed

00:43:01.930 --> 00:43:04.270
for about 40 minutes.

00:43:04.270 --> 00:43:05.770
Got totally skunked.

00:43:05.770 --> 00:43:08.890
Ended up changing our tickets
to leave one day early.

00:43:08.890 --> 00:43:10.000
Had we not changed--

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:11.890
one guy stayed
back and got stuck

00:43:11.890 --> 00:43:14.990
in an airport for seven days.

00:43:14.990 --> 00:43:16.870
So this is us in winter.

00:43:16.870 --> 00:43:19.300
This was probably one of,
like, eight waves surfed

00:43:19.300 --> 00:43:21.160
on the whole trip,
and we drove forever.

00:43:21.160 --> 00:43:23.570
And we're talking, like,
organizing guys from Australia,

00:43:23.570 --> 00:43:28.059
getting guys from
California just to go to--

00:43:28.059 --> 00:43:29.850
and you know, they
believed in our project.

00:43:29.850 --> 00:43:32.016
So when we say, like, you
know, this is our project,

00:43:32.016 --> 00:43:33.910
like, everyone worked.

00:43:33.910 --> 00:43:35.650
It's a quintessential
film crew shot.

00:43:35.650 --> 00:43:38.050
We have a ton of
gear when we travel.

00:43:38.050 --> 00:43:41.110
With the film crew when we made
the film, we had a great team,

00:43:41.110 --> 00:43:43.720
but we also had a lot of gear.

00:43:43.720 --> 00:43:46.090
So this is Davis,
one of the filmers,

00:43:46.090 --> 00:43:48.160
passed out on all
the Pelican cases.

00:43:48.160 --> 00:43:49.790
This is the last section.

00:43:49.790 --> 00:43:54.370
This is Kelly Slater
and John John Florence,

00:43:54.370 --> 00:43:58.060
arguably two of the greatest
surfers of all time.

00:43:58.060 --> 00:43:59.850
I know we're super
short on time.

00:43:59.850 --> 00:44:02.370
We were thinking of
different ways, what

00:44:02.370 --> 00:44:05.100
would be interesting to get
them to converse, to have

00:44:05.100 --> 00:44:06.150
them have a conversation.

00:44:06.150 --> 00:44:08.160
They'd never done a
surf trip together.

00:44:08.160 --> 00:44:10.950
I was like, why not get the two
most competitive surfers ever

00:44:10.950 --> 00:44:13.602
and play a game of chess,
the most competitive--

00:44:13.602 --> 00:44:15.060
one of the most
competitive sports?

00:44:15.060 --> 00:44:16.309
We tried to take them fishing.

00:44:16.309 --> 00:44:17.820
We didn't catch anything.

00:44:17.820 --> 00:44:19.320
Chess, on the other hand--

00:44:19.320 --> 00:44:20.970
and for those of
you that play chess,

00:44:20.970 --> 00:44:22.845
you could probably
see what's happening.

00:44:22.845 --> 00:44:25.920
This image was 100%
inspired by an image

00:44:25.920 --> 00:44:30.570
that Walter Iooss shot,
1964 in the clubhouse

00:44:30.570 --> 00:44:33.992
of two golfers, Arnold
Palmer and Jack Nicklaus.

00:44:33.992 --> 00:44:36.450
It's a black and white image
if you guys have ever seen it.

00:44:36.450 --> 00:44:38.740
It's a direct
derivative of this.

00:44:38.740 --> 00:44:41.370
So this is homage to Walter
Iooss, one of the greatest

00:44:41.370 --> 00:44:42.620
photographers of all time.

00:44:42.620 --> 00:44:43.860
I actually called him
and told him that.

00:44:43.860 --> 00:44:45.360
And he was like, well,
mine was black and white.

00:44:45.360 --> 00:44:46.380
And I was like,
uh, I don't know.

00:44:46.380 --> 00:44:46.880
Its color.

00:44:46.880 --> 00:44:48.500
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:48.500 --> 00:44:50.560
You know, it's not
all about waves.

00:44:50.560 --> 00:44:53.320
It's about exploring,
looking out the windows.

00:44:53.320 --> 00:44:54.820
We've built this
great relationship,

00:44:54.820 --> 00:44:58.170
and I've been able to kind
of share these stories,

00:44:58.170 --> 00:44:59.770
have intimate access to this.

00:44:59.770 --> 00:45:01.350
That's Kelly looking out.

00:45:01.350 --> 00:45:02.630
We flew, we arrived.

00:45:02.630 --> 00:45:04.380
We were meant to go
to a place for a week.

00:45:04.380 --> 00:45:05.790
We ended up being
there for three days.

00:45:05.790 --> 00:45:07.876
This is straight off the
plane, Kelly and John

00:45:07.876 --> 00:45:09.000
looking at an empty lineup.

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:11.190
So a big part of
what we wanted to do

00:45:11.190 --> 00:45:13.830
is photograph these guys
where no one else is.

00:45:13.830 --> 00:45:19.290
So when this project came out,
no one knew that it existed.

00:45:19.290 --> 00:45:22.959
So just getting these two
guys together was a task,

00:45:22.959 --> 00:45:24.750
and making sure there
weren't other cameras

00:45:24.750 --> 00:45:27.210
around was a big task too.

00:45:27.210 --> 00:45:30.900
Kelly was really instrumental
in helping forecast the swell.

00:45:30.900 --> 00:45:34.080
So you know-- and
this was in 2016.

00:45:34.080 --> 00:45:36.480
To get two of the greatest
surfers in the world surfing

00:45:36.480 --> 00:45:38.475
by themselves for three
days with zero cameras

00:45:38.475 --> 00:45:42.030
is kind of a tricky thing to do.

00:45:42.030 --> 00:45:44.550
This is them doing their thing.

00:45:44.550 --> 00:45:47.390
Again, anytime I had the chance
to get two of them together,

00:45:47.390 --> 00:45:49.420
I would.

00:45:49.420 --> 00:45:52.096
Underwater is probably my
favorite way to shoot images.

00:45:52.096 --> 00:45:53.220
I apologize if I'm rushing.

00:45:53.220 --> 00:45:55.572
I know we're short on time.

00:45:55.572 --> 00:45:57.780
These next two images are
probably my favorite images

00:45:57.780 --> 00:45:58.800
from the project.

00:45:58.800 --> 00:46:02.605
This one of Kelly is underwater.

00:46:02.605 --> 00:46:04.440
It was shot with a
really wide angle lens,

00:46:04.440 --> 00:46:06.990
but it was shot with a
rectilinear lens rather than

00:46:06.990 --> 00:46:07.500
a fisheye.

00:46:07.500 --> 00:46:11.130
Most fisheye lens are
real bulbous, like a GoPro

00:46:11.130 --> 00:46:12.390
or even like a Canon fisheye.

00:46:12.390 --> 00:46:14.760
I did an automotive shoot
where we were tracking

00:46:14.760 --> 00:46:16.672
on the side of a bridge.

00:46:16.672 --> 00:46:18.630
And I remember after the
shoot, I called Kelly.

00:46:18.630 --> 00:46:20.504
I was like, I just did
this automotive shoot,

00:46:20.504 --> 00:46:22.230
and there's this lens.

00:46:22.230 --> 00:46:23.020
It's amazing.

00:46:23.020 --> 00:46:25.860
And we built a water housing
and a port just for this lens.

00:46:25.860 --> 00:46:28.440
And we waited two years for
the waves to get good for us

00:46:28.440 --> 00:46:30.670
to go to this location
with this place in mind.

00:46:30.670 --> 00:46:32.850
And when we got this
image, we were like, OK.

00:46:32.850 --> 00:46:34.419
It was worth it.

00:46:34.419 --> 00:46:36.210
This is one of the few
photos that hangs up

00:46:36.210 --> 00:46:38.720
on his wall at his house.

00:46:38.720 --> 00:46:41.940
There's also the cover
of "SURFER" magazine.

00:46:41.940 --> 00:46:43.800
This image shows the art.

00:46:43.800 --> 00:46:45.340
So like I said
earlier, each surfer

00:46:45.340 --> 00:46:46.840
was partner with a
different artist.

00:46:46.840 --> 00:46:49.006
This is the art by Richard
Phillips out in New York.

00:46:49.006 --> 00:46:54.150
So we wanted this to be a
multilayered experience.

00:46:54.150 --> 00:46:56.920
Not just surfing, not just
waves, not just music.

00:46:56.920 --> 00:47:00.030
So with the project, we had an
original score, original crew,

00:47:00.030 --> 00:47:01.020
original artwork.

00:47:01.020 --> 00:47:02.680
And all the boards
are at my house.

00:47:02.680 --> 00:47:05.400
So when we do these art shows,
you can go touch the boards,

00:47:05.400 --> 00:47:10.051
feel the boards
see them firsthand.

00:47:10.051 --> 00:47:10.550
All right.

00:47:10.550 --> 00:47:12.800
This is the last
image and probably one

00:47:12.800 --> 00:47:17.420
of the images we're most proud
of, we're most grateful for.

00:47:17.420 --> 00:47:19.691
Kelly had had that wave before.

00:47:19.691 --> 00:47:20.690
Not the above water one.

00:47:20.690 --> 00:47:22.539
The below water one.

00:47:22.539 --> 00:47:24.830
And earlier in the day, he
was like, I was in the water

00:47:24.830 --> 00:47:27.200
and I ducked over, and I
watched John pass by me.

00:47:27.200 --> 00:47:29.450
He's like, is that what you
were trying to photograph?

00:47:29.450 --> 00:47:30.370
And I said, yeah.

00:47:30.370 --> 00:47:31.520
I'm like, it looks so cool.

00:47:31.520 --> 00:47:32.967
The water's so clear.

00:47:32.967 --> 00:47:33.800
And he's like, cool.

00:47:33.800 --> 00:47:37.595
And then he was paddling back
out after that previous wave,

00:47:37.595 --> 00:47:38.970
and John was
already in the tube.

00:47:38.970 --> 00:47:40.550
And he's like, I'm going to
duck dive in front of you.

00:47:40.550 --> 00:47:41.537
And I'm like, no!

00:47:41.537 --> 00:47:42.620
John's got to [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:42.620 --> 00:47:44.000
We hadn't got a good photo yet.

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:46.870
And you know, sometimes these
swells only last half a day.

00:47:46.870 --> 00:47:49.790
So Kelly duck dived in front of
me, and I'm thinking, oh, man.

00:47:49.790 --> 00:47:50.780
He blocked it.

00:47:50.780 --> 00:47:52.440
I don't know what to think.

00:47:52.440 --> 00:47:54.546
And he comes up, and he's
like, that was the one.

00:47:54.546 --> 00:47:55.884
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:55.884 --> 00:47:57.740
And so I'm just
thinking, oh, man.

00:47:57.740 --> 00:48:00.110
He totally-- this guy's so
competitive, he blocked him.

00:48:00.110 --> 00:48:02.568
He totally blocked the shot,
because he knew he got a shot.

00:48:02.568 --> 00:48:05.570
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:05.570 --> 00:48:06.740
I went back to the boat.

00:48:06.740 --> 00:48:08.090
I sat in the corner of the boat.

00:48:08.090 --> 00:48:09.534
I undid the housing.

00:48:09.534 --> 00:48:11.450
And I'm just-- you always
start back to front.

00:48:11.450 --> 00:48:12.140
You never start at the front.

00:48:12.140 --> 00:48:14.210
The front's never good
with photo shoots.

00:48:14.210 --> 00:48:16.126
And this was the last
wave before we went back

00:48:16.126 --> 00:48:16.790
to the boat.

00:48:16.790 --> 00:48:18.140
And I was like, oh.

00:48:18.140 --> 00:48:20.090
I'm like, block, block, block.

00:48:20.090 --> 00:48:21.470
Oh, we have something here.

00:48:21.470 --> 00:48:22.225
And he walked by.

00:48:22.225 --> 00:48:24.100
John walked by, and he
was like, what's that?

00:48:24.100 --> 00:48:25.700
And I'm like, I think we have
something kind of special

00:48:25.700 --> 00:48:27.400
here if this thing's in focus.

00:48:27.400 --> 00:48:29.930
And then Kelly walked by, and
he's like, that's the one.

00:48:29.930 --> 00:48:30.480
I told you.

00:48:30.480 --> 00:48:31.270
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:31.270 --> 00:48:33.012
it ended up being
the cover of the book

00:48:33.012 --> 00:48:34.220
and the cover of the project.

00:48:34.220 --> 00:48:37.220
And to me, this really
summed up "Proximity."

00:48:37.220 --> 00:48:40.960
Again, at the time, John
had not won a world title.

00:48:40.960 --> 00:48:42.770
Kelly had won 11.

00:48:42.770 --> 00:48:45.170
I hate to say old guard,
but the older generation

00:48:45.170 --> 00:48:47.590
watching the newer generation.

00:48:47.590 --> 00:48:51.730
And so there's a lot
of symbolism with that.

00:48:51.730 --> 00:48:52.430
Thank you guys.

00:48:52.430 --> 00:48:53.570
I apologize I rushed.

00:48:53.570 --> 00:48:55.045
I know there's questions.

00:48:55.045 --> 00:48:56.320
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:48:56.320 --> 00:48:58.750
TODD GLASER: I do
still shoot on film.

00:48:58.750 --> 00:49:02.240
Not all the time,
but for this project,

00:49:02.240 --> 00:49:04.005
I probably went through about--

00:49:04.005 --> 00:49:08.030
I probably shot
half of it on film.

00:49:08.030 --> 00:49:09.750
Most of the color
images are all digital,

00:49:09.750 --> 00:49:12.530
and most of the black and
white images are all on film.

00:49:12.530 --> 00:49:15.560
I really just try to kind
of simplify my process

00:49:15.560 --> 00:49:17.830
by bringing less gear.

00:49:17.830 --> 00:49:20.780
It's a lot to travel with,
especially when you're

00:49:20.780 --> 00:49:22.250
the Sherpa carrying
all the stuff.

00:49:22.250 --> 00:49:24.100
[LAUGHTER]

00:49:24.100 --> 00:49:26.830
My back appreciates not
carrying as much film stuff.

00:49:26.830 --> 00:49:28.610
But yeah.

00:49:28.610 --> 00:49:30.320
I'm trying to build
a darkroom right now.

00:49:30.320 --> 00:49:31.111
I love shooting it.

00:49:31.111 --> 00:49:32.627
I miss the tangibility of it.

